entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued January 9 at 5:27AM CST by NWS Hastings NE
entry.summary:
Through around 10 or 11 AM, at least limited areas of fog, some perhaps dense and reducing visibility to around 1/4 mile or less, will continue to affect or eventually develop within portions of primarily Smith, Osborne, Jewell and Mitchell counties. Any fog that does develop will gradually move out or dissipate from west- to-east ahead of an approaching cold front. In the meantime, motorists venturing out this morning should be prepared to encounter potential fog, and visibility that could vary considerably over short distances.
At this time, it is unclear whether the coverage of truly dense fog will become widespread enough to perhaps justify a formal Dense Fog Advisory, but conditions will continue to be monitored.
entry.cap:areaDesc: Smith; Jewell; Osborne; Mitchell

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued January 9 at 12:54PM ChST by NWS Tiyan GU
entry.summary:
Choppy seas and elevated surf continue across the Marshall Islands due to building northeast winds and swell, along with long-period north swell generated by storms moving across the north Pacific. Seas and surf will build further, probably peaking on Friday, then diminishing over the weekend.
Model guidance indicates the north swell will move through with a period 12 to 15 seconds and height of at least 5 to 7 feet, creating hazardous surf around 12 feet with minor coastal inundation up to a foot, especially along north facing shores during high tide. All of the atolls with lagoons, such as Majuro and Kwajalein, should watch for inundation along shores facing into the lagoon, especially shores facing northward as high surf pushes water into the lagoon from the north. All islands of the Marshall Islands have the potential to see impacts from this north swell event, so be mindful when near the water or traveling along roads near north facing shores.
Also, with the expected increase in trade winds and swell waves during this same time, inter-island travel in small boats will be hazardous with seas of at least 10 feet and higher at times, and winds around 25 knots.
Residents should monitor local sea conditions and forecasts through the end of this week. Be alert for minor flooding and debris on roads and property near shores, along with hazardous surfing, swimming, and boating conditions. Stay up to date with information from your Weather Service Office in Majuro, and any information shared from local emergency management offices. The latest Majuro forecasts can be found at weather.gov/gum/PublicForecasts.

entry.summary:
ESFAFC
Recent and continuing warm weather and widespread rainfall have led to rising creek and stream levels from the Kenai Peninsula north into the Mat-Su Valleys. Overflow has been reported on creeks and over existing trails. Increased streamflows may also lead to localized ice jams. Those traveling on backcountry trails are encouraged to take extra caution around area streams, rivers and trails, as water may degrade ice and create difficult or hazardous conditions.
Additional warm and wet weather is expected this weekend, which may lead to additional river rises and overflow conditions.

entry.summary: ANOTHER STRONG WET FRONT IS EXPECTED FOR THE PANHANDLE THURSDAY AND FRIDAY. entry.title: Air Quality Alert issued January 8 at 9:45AM MST by NWS Phoenix AZ
entry.summary:
The Arizona Department of Environmental Quality (ADEQ) has issued a PM-10 High Pollution Advisory for the Yuma area through tomorrow.
An episode of strong and gusty winds is forecast to generate widespread blowing dust that may result in local PM-10 concentrations that pose a health risk. Adverse health effects increase as air quality deteriorates.
Coarse particulate matter - also known as PM-10 - is an air contaminant that can aggravate heart and lung disease conditions, especially in older adults, children, and those with asthma. A decrease in physical activity is recommended.
Consolidate your travel, stabilize loose soils, slow down or avoid travel on dirt roads, reduce or eliminate fireplace use, and avoid using gas-powered lawn equipment.
For details on this High Pollution Advisory, visit the ADEQ internet site at www.azdeq.gov/forecast/yuma or call 602-771-2300.
